better than that. I like this man's, what he's 
doing more than I did for Tiger Teague. Graham,

35:11.493 --> 35:13.636
you're talking about? Graham, yeah. I have a 
letter from him every week or two. Oh, that's

35:17.600 --> 35:25.751
wonderful.

35:26.492 --> 35:28.715
You were called into World War II. How did the city, 
did the city do anything to prepare for war? Did the

35:34.824 --> 35:40.873
city, did College Station do anything to prepare 
for war, for World War II? Oh yeah, yeah. We had our

35:44.658 --> 35:51.206
committees set up, and we had a lot of people. We 
lived right across the street from somebody who

35:51.947 --> 36:02.922
dug a pit where they could go in case of a bomb threat 
or a bomb. They started bombing anywhere, and they

36:05.104 --> 36:11.813
dug a pit and stocked it with so forth, our 
next-door neighbor. So there was a movement there

36:13.244 --> 36:15.707
to do that. A few people did it, not many of

36:15.727 --> 36:20.693
them. I never was very much excited over that. I 
didn't much think that they were going to do

36:24.879 --> 36:31.708
anything like that at that time. I don't think 
they're going to do anything like that now. I think

36:35.532 --> 36:39.017
that they wouldn't bother small towns, 
certainly. They'd have to, they'd have to hit the

36:39.377 --> 36:43.082
big cities though. In order to win the war, they'd 
have to do that.

36:59.047 --> 37:10.639
Well, is there anything else that you might want to 
add about what the concentration was like before

36:59.047 --> 37:10.639
or just your term as mayor that I haven't 
questioned you about?

37:14.045 --> 37:15.587
Everybody's nice to us. We have a lot of friends and 
we like it. I

37:22.394 --> 37:32.426
don't take any dish though in their duties. I don't 
support anybody that's running for office at

37:33.587 --> 37:41.436
College Station. I don't know enough about them to 
do that. And as far as I can tell, everything's

37:47.320 --> 37:51.625
going along very well.

37:56.491 --> 38:05.482
Now, nationally, I'm taking more interest 
because we can't print money. And the state of

38:06.624 --> 38:09.888
Texas or no other state can print money. But the 
United States government can print money And all

38:14.069 --> 38:17.514
they have to do is to print a little more of it. 
They've printed too much of it already.

38:22.342 --> 38:32.398
The more money they put in circulation, if they pay 
off debts, and if they pay it, we draw Social

38:22.342 --> 38:32.398
Security. We also draw a retired army. I stayed in 
the army between, I stayed active between the two

38:37.306 --> 38:41.933
world wars.

38:45.710 --> 39:06.985
I went to camp two weeks, practically every year, 
and over there we'd have a bunch of A&M

38:45.710 --> 39:06.985
artillerymen that graduated here, and they were 
over there as second lieutenants, or maybe if they

38:45.710 --> 39:06.985
were a little older they were first lieutenants, 
or maybe they might be a captain of the team. That

39:07.045 --> 39:09.869
would be at the A&M artillery group. I was with the 
field artillery.

39:14.093 --> 39:15.675
We had two weeks training there. We worked hard and 
we had a lot of fun together. We always played a

39:19.318 --> 39:20.359
little. We always had a nice little party at the end 
of the thing and it was just a nice experience. And

39:28.047 --> 39:36.034
when World War II came along, they didn't want us. I 
don't think they wanted us. When I got this call, it

39:38.637 --> 39:42.801
says now you don't have to come unless you want to. I 
think they had really rather that we didn't come,

39:43.372 --> 39:52.766
because I was too old to go overseas already, 52. 
And I didn't know that. I didn't know that I wasn't

39:58.534 --> 40:07.287
going to be allowed to go overseas, but they sent me 
and seven other old colonels who had been loyal and

40:08.060 --> 40:12.825
worked good hard with an outfit between the new 
wars. They felt like they just owed it to us to give

40:12.885 --> 40:17.890
us a chance if they wanted to come to come. So we did. 
There were seven of us and we went up to school and we

40:20.473 --> 40:25.458
went through the basic course again. I'd already 
been through the artillery school 1917-18 up at

40:25.498 --> 40:36.109
Fort Sill and then

40:38.401 --> 40:44.690
This time they sent us back and we took the basic 
course, which is much easier than that war course

40:38.401 --> 40:44.690
was. And then after they took the basic course, 
they didn't have anything for us to do, so they just

40:45.591 --> 40:52.481
kept us up there on a board. To do this, investigate 
that, do this, that, and the other, and there's

40:53.162 --> 40:58.089
always something like that going on. And then to 
pick people who have been drafted and they want to

40:58.149 --> 41:07.783
go to a cadet camp where they maybe be second 
lieutenants. get ready to get a promotion you see

41:08.860 --> 41:26.397
and so we we had recommended these people that the 
captains had sent to us we had talked to them and and

41:08.860 --> 41:26.397
if we felt like they offered material we had 
recommended they go to this school things like

41:08.860 --> 41:26.397
that they kept us done for a good many months

41:29.228 --> 41:33.595
And then they finally decided, after all, they 
didn't have anything else much for us to do. And

41:34.797 --> 41:39.404
they sent us up there, and they sent us to different 
places. Sent me to Fort Jackson over in North

41:39.464 --> 41:43.930
Carolina. That's where they ought to have left me 
through the balance of the war. That's where we

41:47.736 --> 41:55.388
were training the recruits, people to fill in, to 
fill gaps in casualties overseas. But they

41:56.043 --> 42:07.354
decided they'd better send me off there to 
something after a year or so, and I went to 30th

41:56.043 --> 42:07.354
Division. And they were training, getting ready 
to go overseas, to Oklahoma, Tennessee. And I was

42:14.120 --> 42:19.004
with them there, and then they sent us up, finished 
that, they sent us up to Indianapolis. And we did a

42:20.166 --> 42:24.970
little more work over there, and then they sent 
them overseas. And here I was about 52, and there

42:25.152 --> 42:28.475
was a cutoff. No, can't go. And so I went, I said, 
I've been in the Army now for a good many months, and

42:30.617 --> 42:47.534
I'm just drawing colonel's pay and doing 
something my captain can do, inspect a mess or

42:30.617 --> 42:47.534
something like that, or do other things. And I 
didn't come in the Army to do that kind of stuff, and

42:48.135 --> 42:51.799
I won't go home. And I've got a job back at A&M 
College. And they turned me down. They did? Yeah.

42:58.086 --> 43:03.031
And so they offered me a place to go to West Point. 
They said, you go up there and be a teacher at West

43:03.272 --> 43:05.594
Point. I said, well, I'm not the type. I'm a field 
soldier. I'm not the type that has a press blouse

43:09.078 --> 43:14.404
every week and shiny. And I just don't fit in to go to 
West Point. I'm way beyond that in the Army. the way

43:22.561 --> 43:27.426
I, what I think that an army man at my age should be 
doing. And finally, finally I just wrote him

